{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_clarkia_ver01/data/sn84036287/00340581830/1938031101/0074.xml":{"full_text":"S\nCARBON COUNTY NEWS\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CARBON COUNTY AND CITY OF RED LODGE\nRED LODGE DAILY nkus\nVOL. 3, NO. 296\nCARBON COUNTY NEWS\nVOL. XV, NO. 2.\nRED LODGE, CARBON COUNTY, MONTANA.\nMARCH 1, 1936.\nDERBY ATTENDED\nBY ABOUT 7,000\nPERSONS SUNDAY\nCeley Baum Captures First\nPlace; Other Acts\nPleasing\nRed Lodge thrilled to an exhibi\ntion of dog racing here Sunday\nwhich marked the first demonstra\ntion of a dog derby ever to appear\nin Red Lodge.\nAlthough run on snowless streets,\nthe derby was well attended by\nthrongs from outside of the city.\nIt was estimated that approximate\nly 7,606 lined the streets to watch\nthe event.\nCeley Baum, Ashton, Ida., was\nclocked first in the major event in\nthe time of 29 minutes and one\nsecond. Lloyd Van Sickle took sec\nond and Bill Zink of West Yellow\nstone, Mont., was given third place\nmoney.\nFirst prize of $500 went to\nBaum, second prize of $300 went\nto Van Sickle, while Bill Zink took\nthird honors with a $200 booty.\nGaynell Loughney was declared\nSnow Queen and she was so pre\nsented at a dance held at the Labor\nTemple Saturday night.\nWheels were used on sleds in\nthe dog derby, but that didn't de\ntract from interest in the event.\nHundreds applauded Thula Gee\nlan's efforts as she circled the\ncourse. She was the only woman\ndriver in the race.\nPreceding the main event was a\nrace called a \"Kids Derby,\nmarathon which resulted in Bobby\nMartin taking first; Roy Abney,\nsecond, and Bobby White third.\nOfficial starters for the big\nevent were Bill Moore, Jr., H. A.\nGraves, Robert Bealmear and M.\nJ. Schanck.\nOfficial time keepers were Art\nTrenerry of Billings and A. M.\nHartwig of Red Lodge.\nJudges were as follows: A1 Ran\nkin, Billings; E. P. Conwell, H. C.\nOlcott, J. J. Gerondale, Dr. E. M.\nAdams, Dr. J. C. F. Siegfriedt, H.\nA. Simmons and J. P. Plunkett.\nCapably policing the grounds\nwere Chief of Police J. H. McAllis\nter, his assistants, and members\nof the state highway patrol.\nMany liked the act of \"Cowboy\",\na diving act of a dog trained by\nMr. E. Mayott.\nThe snow shoe race ended in a\ntie between Engler of Red Lodge\nand Baum of Ashton, Idaho.\nWide approval was given\nRed Lodge band, which provided\nmusic just preceding the race.\nA military atmosphere was fur\nyy\na\nthe\nnished by the Carbon county high\nschool \"peppers\" and the Moose\nDrum and Bugle corps.\nTo be congratulated on success\nof the event are D. W. Columbus,\npresident of the Red Lodge Winter\nSports association; Harley Weydt,\nvice president, and Gus Foltz, sec\nretary-treasurer.\nPICK TOOLEY AS\nHOUSING LEADER\nDr. L. H. Tooley, Red Lodge\npostmaster, has accepted a request\nthat he be voluntary chairman of\na Better Housing committee for\nthis community, according to an\nannouncement made here today.\nThis position is set up in ac\ncordance with the new national\nhousing act recently passed by con\ngress and signed by President\nRoosevelt. Under the old housing\nact, Dr. Tooley was also chairman\nof the local group.\nIn requesting that he act as head\nof the committee, Stewart McDon\nald, federal housing administrator,\nwired the postmaster as follows:\n\"The passage of the new national\nhousing act opens the way for a\nreal residential construction pro\ngram which should carry with it a\nbusiness revival. The\ngenuine\nPresident asks that we again re\nquest your participation as volun\ntary chaii'man to immediately\nsponsor this revival in your com\nmunity and get its full benefits\nimmediately.\"\nTooley wired his acceptance.\nThe borrower must have an as\nsured income and demonstrate his\nability to pay, the act states. He\nmust own the property or have a\nlease running at least six months\nlonger than the term of the loan.\nIndividuals, partnerships or cor\nporations may qualify.\nAmounts up to $10,000 may be\nborrowed\nto improve existing\nstructures, Tooley said,\ncharges, including interest, cannot\nbe more than the equivalent of $5\ndiscount per $106 original face val\nue of a one year note, payable in\n(Continued on Page 8)\nTotal\nDOG DERBY A SUCCESS\nRed Lodge and environs can be nothing but pleased at\nthe splendid success of the First Annual Dog Derby held\nhere Sunday. Especially satisfactory was the manner in\nwhich citizens cooperated to put over the show.\nOf course there were a few who ridiculed the derby\nfrom the beginning, and there was also a certain quota\nthat was luke warm in the endeavor, but, all in all, most\npersons lent their best efforts to make the project\nsuccessful.\nIt is easy to understand why the Ashton, Idaho, derby\nis acclaimed as it is, when one meets the persons who rep\nresent that gracious little city. W. O. Harris, president of\nthe American Dog Derby association; W. L. Hansen, vice\npresident, and C. C. Davidson and H. A. Toolson, directors,\nwere present for the event and their counsel was greatly\nappreciated. The work of Warren Cordingly, also of Ash\nton, in mapping out the race track was of importance in\nm,aking the'event the success it was.\nTo enumerate all those from Red Lodge that contributed\nwould take too much space here. Suffice it to say that prac\ntically without exception the merchants put their shoul\nders to the wheel in a way that insured a happy culmina\ntion to the goal set down by the Red Lodge Winter Sports\nassociation.\nWhile citizens are in accord in making the derby an an\nnual event, concentration is now placed on the annual ro\ndeo which will be held here on July 2, 3,and 4. All those in\nterested in the rodeo are heartily urged to attend meetings\nof the association to add their efforts towards putting the\nannual event across.\nIn conclusion we want to congratulate the officers of\nthe Red Lodge Winter Sports association who worked so\ntirelessly to make the show a success, They are D. W. Co\nlumbus, president; Harley Weydt, vice president, and Gus\nFoltz, secretary-treasurer. Other officials of the organiza\ntion did their share as well.\nINTERESTING BUSINESS SESSION HELD\nBY ROD AND GUN CLUB WEDNESDAY\nRed Lodge Rod and Gun club,\nmembers \"caught up\" on their bus\niness in a lengthy session at the\nElks home here Wednesday night,\nBill Curran, president of the organ\nization, was in charge of the gath\nermg.\nIn response to a communication\nfrom John W. Schofield, state sup\nerintendent of fisheries, the club\nwent on record as backing propos\ned fishing regulations. These in\nclude recommendations that there\nbe no fishing from 9:30 p. m. to\n4 a. m., that the angling season\nbe set from May 21 to November\n30 in open wat\u00e8rs, and that game\nfish limit be fixed at 15 fish per\nday, not to exceed 15 pounds and\none fish.\nO. P. Roberts, Carbon county\nextension agent, reported on pest\ncontrol work and accomplishments\nof 4-H boys in this regard. The\nclub voted $20, an increase of $5\nover recent years, to aid in the\neradication of magpies. George L.\nThroop protested against the use\nof poison in killing coyotes and\nmagpies, maintaining that poison\nalso kills fox and harmless birds.\nThe desirability of distributing\nsalt for deer and elk was discuss\ned. Carl Benson, deputy game\nwarden, stated that the state fish\nand game commission has agreed\nto furnish the salt and that it will\nbe placed in this area soon.\nA motion was passed recom\nmending to the fish and game com\nmission that Carl Benson, deputy\ngame warden, be retained in this\narea permanently and not assign\ned to special duties in other sec\ntors of the state. It was the opin\nion of the club members that the\nsituation in Carbon county is such\nthat a permanent warden is nec\nessary. The sportsmen decided to\ninvite J. A. Weaver, state game\nwarden, to visit the county on an\ninspection trip.\nF. I. Johnson reported on the re\ncent wild life federation at Great\nFalls. Mr. Johnson, who has been\nappointed Carbon county chairman\nfor the National Wild Life week\nbeginning March 20, announced\nthat he is in possession of game\nstamps to be sold at a cent each.\nJACOBSON RITES\nNOTED THIS WEEK\nMrs. Jacob Jacobson, 55, a resi\ndent of Red Lodge for the past 23\nyears, died at her home Saturday\nfollowing a paralytic stroke.\nFuneral services were held at 2\np. m. Tuesday at the Martin Funer\nal home, with the Rev. A. B. Cor\nnelson officiating. Burial was at\nRed Lodce Cemetery.\nMrs. Jacobson was born in Swed\nen on Oct. 4, 1882.\nSurvivors include the husband,\none son, Gerald Peterson of Red\nLodge; one brother, Ellis Wedin of\nBillings, and two sisters, Mrs.\nSwea Nelson of Sweden, and Miss\nAustra Wedin, also of Sweden.\nOf each dollar taken in 35 cents\ngoes to the Montana Wild Life\nfederation, he said, the remainder\ngoing to the national federation.\nH. C. Olcott, a member of the\nstate's Wild Life federation legis\nlative committee, explained two\nproposed bills designed to \"take\nthe fish and game commission out\nof polities.\" Both suggested bills\nprovide for dividing the state into\neither five or seven districts. One\nsuggested measure stipulates each\ndistrict elect a commissioner by\npopular vote, the other provides\nthat commissioners be nominated\nby rod and gun clubs and that the\ngovernor appoint from this list.\nAfter considerable discussion it\nwas agreed that efforts should be\nmade to place boulders and logs\nin Rock Creek to provide a resting\npl ac _ e f\u00b0 r W PA labor foi this\nproject was considered,\nA motion was passed setting the\nfourth Tuesday of each month as\na regular meeting date.\nCommittees appointed by Mr.\nCurran are as follows:\nFish planting: A. D. Whitcomb,\nchairman; Leo Spogen, Lou Mary\nott, Joe Enrico and I. J. Hares.\nMembership G. L. Throop,\nchairman; Jim Castagne, Steve\nKotar, A. G. Showerman, Vic Ko\ntar, Joe Meyer, George Sukar, G.\nB. Foltz, A. M. Hartwig Hugh Mc\nLuskie, Bill Larkin, Jr., and Bob\nBealmear.\nW. W. Flashman suggested that\nefforts be made to plant smelt in\nCooney dam.\nEMERGENCY LOANS\nTAKEN AT JOLIET\nApplications for emergency crop\nand feed loans for 1938 are now\nbeing received at Joliet by Mr.\nBradley, Field Supervisor of the\nEmergency Crop and Feed Loan\nSection of the Farm Credit Admin\nistration.\nThe loans will be made, as in\nthe past, only to farmers who can\nnot obtain credit from any other\nsource. The money loaned will be\nlimited to the farmer's immediate\nand actual cash needs for growing\nhis 1938 crops or for the purchase\nof feed for livestock, and the\namount which may be loaned to\nany one farmer in 1938 may not\nexceed $400.\nFarmers who can obtain the\nfunds they need from an individual,\nproduction credit association, bank,\nor other concern are not eligible\nfor crop and feed loans from the\nEmergency Crop and Feed Loan\nSection of the Farm Credit Admin\nistration. The loans will not be\nmade to standard rehabilitation\nclients whose current needs are\nprovided for by the Farm Security\nAdministration, formerly known as\nthe Resettlement Administration.\nAs in the past, farmers who ob\ntain emergency crop and feed loans\nwill give as security a first lien on\nthe crop financed, or a first lien on\n(Continued on Page 8)\nThe Week's\nNews in Review\nState\nLivingston\u2014Restoration of $38,\n500 of a total of $41,000 withdrawn\nfrom the national park service in\nYellowstone national park last\nyear is announced by Joseph Joffe,\nassistant to the superintendent.\nBillings\u2014Jose Ac lilar receives\nthe maximum sentence of six\nmonths in Yellowstone county jail\nand is fined $500 by District Judge\nBen Harwood when he pleads guil\nty to a charge of possession of\nnarcotics.\nHelena\u2014The state railroad and\npublic service commission, whose\nmembers also are the Montana\ntrades commission, state that re\nports circulating in western Mon\ntana to the effect that the commis\nsion has set minimum prices on\ncigarettes are \"false.\"\nHarlowton\u2014Work of excavating\nfor the basement and foundation\nfor the new $106,060 high school\nis progressing rapidly.\nButte\u2014\"The richest hill on\nearth\" is closed tight to gambling\nupon orders termed as \"myterious.\"\nHardin\u2014 T. N. Mayfield of Mans\nfield, Wash., announces plans for\ndevelopment of a bentonite deposit\non the Crow Indian reservaion, 40\nmiles south of Hardin. Bentonite is\nmineral clay.\nBelfry\u2014Pete Vavich, manager of\nthe invitational girls' basketball\ntournament held here, announces\nthe following all-tourney team:\nRuth Nelson of Worden, B. Sco\nville of Columbus and L. McCready\nof Joliet, forwards; K. Powers of\nColumbus, E. Hatten of Joliet and\nMary Jackson of Belfry, guards.\nHigh scorer of the meet was B.\nScoville of Columbus who totaled\n52 points.\nLewistown\u2014The Central Mon\ntana Press association as a division\n(Continued on Page 4)\nConcert and Dance\nFixed for Roberts\nThe Roberts band will present\na concert and d? at the Rob\nerts high school gymnasium the\nnight of March 17. The concert,\nstarting at 8 p. m., will consist of\nclassical and semi-classical num\nbers and will last for 1 hours.\nBand members will also play for\nthe dance.\nSPEAKERS FOR AG\nPROGRAM PICKED\nExplanations of the changes in\nthe 1938 agricultural conservation\nprogram will be given county com\nmitteemen and county extension\nagents at a series of district meet\nings to be held in the state start\ning March 11, announces J. C. Tay\nlor, Montana Extension service di\nrector. After the district meetings,\ncommunity meetings will be held\nto acquaint farmers with these\nchanges.\nThe changes to be explained at\nthe district meetings are designed\nto bring the AAA program for this\nyear fully into line with specific\nprovisions of the recently enacted\nAgricultural Adjustment Act of\n1938, Taylor said.\nEach of the meetings will be of\ntwo days duration and the speak\ners will be A. J. Borton, executive\nsecretary of the state committee;\nW. H. Lamphere, extension econ\nomist; R. E. Bodley, county agent\nleader, and Director Taylor.\nThe schedule of meetings fol\nlows: Billings and Missoula, March\n11 and 12; Bozeman and Miles\nCity, March 14 and 15; Wolf\nPoint and Great Falls, March 17\nand 18.\nSince two of the meetings will\nbe held simultaneously, Borton and\nBodley will have charge of the\nmeetings at Billings, Miles City\nand Wolf Point, while those at Mis\nsoula, Bozeman and Great Falls\nwill be in charge of Lamphere and\nTaylor.\nWPA IS BUILDING\nSOFTBALL GROUND\nA crew of recreational project\nworkers\nstruction of a softball diamond on\na plot of city land between 7th and\n8th streets on the banks of Rock\nCreek.\nWalter E. Taylor, state supervis\nfor WPA recreation, is here to\ntake charge of the project.\nIt is planned to conduct a city\nsoftball league along lines similar\nto the basketball league of the past\nwinter.\nThoi-day started con\nor\nGOOD BYE, BARREL!\nA\n'PO L\n\ns\nITS ALL\n1 HAVE\nL BVT.\nm\ni.\n4?\nMW\n'M\n\nJy//T\nm\n1\n\u25a0I\nm\n1\nw.\n\nj*\n\n?J)\nr\n\u00e0\n\nJ\nf\nBUSINESSMAN PLEA\nGIVEN ROOSEVELT\nIn a spirit of cooperation, busi\nness and labor leaders and city of\nficials of St. Louis have dispatched\na joint plea to President Roose\nvelt and the Missouri delegation in\nCongress asking that steps be tak\nen to relieve the uncertainty over\nfuture government policies.\nThese uncertainties were de\nscribed by the leaders of the meet\ning as \"the principal contributing\ncause of increasing unemploy\nment.\nThe meeting was called upon the\nsuggestion of labor leaders on the\nheels of publication of figures,\nshowing a sharp increase in Janu\nary employment compared with a\nsimilar period in 1937.\nThe resolution containing the\nplea to the Washington officials\nread as follows:\n\"Whereas a meeting was this\nday had in the City Hall in the\ncity of St. Louis of a large group\ncomposed of leaders of labor, bus\niness and industry and the muni\ncipal government, and\n\"Whereas, it was the unanimous\nopinion that the unemployment\nsituation in the city of St. Louis is\nand has been, for the past several\nmonths, increasing to an alarming\n\nextent, and\n\"Whereas, it was the unanimous\nopinion of those present at said\nmeeting that the principal contrib\nuting cause of such increasing un\nemployment is the uncertainty in\nbusiness and industrial circles as\nto the future policies and course\nof the government, in this distress\ning situation which prevents gov\nernment, business and labor from\ncooperating and capital from se\ncuring a fair return and labor's\nfair wage.\n\"Now be it resolved that this\nmeeting hereby implores the Pres\nident of the United States and all\nrepresentatives in Congress to take\nsuch steps as may be necessary to\nrelieve the uncertainty of mind\nprevailing in labor, business and\nindustrial circles.\"\nHYDE IS WINNER\nOVER AL WEBSTER\nBilly Hyde, Red Lodge's clever\nbattler, outboxed A1 Webster, Bil\nlings \"Iron Man\" in a 10 round\nlings\nheadliner to cop the final event in\nthe Dog Derby fight card held here\nSunday night. 500 fans witnessed\nthe card. Hyde clearly mastered his\nopponent, who grew visibly tired\nas the rounds went on. Judges for\nthe event were H. P. Cassidy and\nYule Rees, while Bert Castellano,\nreferee for all the bouts, gave no\ndissenting decision.\nBilly was master of the situa\ntion all the way and, while some\nrounds were draws, he dominated\nmost of the cantos with his punch\ning and feinting.\nWebster was handicapped con\nsiderably due to a sprained shoul\nder sustained in the third round.\nThe Billings battler struggled\ngamely, nevertheless, and gave\nBilly a fight all the way. The\ncrowd cheered the veteran fisti\ncuffer as he gave a splendid per\nformance.\nThis newspaper gives Billy the\nfirst, third, fifth, sixth, ninth and\ntenth rounds to Hyde. The rest\nwere draws.\n(Continued on Page 8)\nFLYING SQUADRON\nVISITS THURSDAY\nDetails of compensation rights,\nveterans' preferential privileges,\nhospitalization benefits and other\nmatters were discussed by two\nmembers of a \"flying squadron,\nrepresenting veterans bureaus, and\nCarbon county ex-soldiers and\nsailors in a session at the city hall\nThursday afternoon.\nHere as guests of Carbon Amer\nican Legion Post No. 17 were Herb\nKibler, Helena, adjutant of the\nMontana department of the Leg\nion, and Herman Dokken, Bozeman,\ndepartment vice commander.\nA lunch at Natali's cafe at noon\npreceded the business session.\nActing as a committee to work\n\u25a0with the two visitors were Henry\nAlbert, Jimmy Atherton and Jim\nFairgrieves, Red Lodge ex-service\nmen, and William Gullickson, W.\nJohn Fouse and Paul Lose of the\nBelfry Legionnaires.\nInvestigating claims of ex-sei\nvicemen, Kibler and Dokken visit\ned at Huntley Wednesday night,\nHardin Thursday night, and were\nscheduled to meet at Columbus to\nday.\nyy\nWhile the squadron visits\nsponsored by the American Leg\nion, the meetings are for the bene\nare\nfit of Spanish-American war vet\nerans, regular army men and their\ndependent wives, children and par\nents.\nDISCUSS BUILDING\nOF NEW CITY HALL!\nPossibilities of securing a new\ncity hall were discussed by mem\nbers of the Red Lodge city council\nin regular session here Tuesday\nnight. Aldermen agreed to hold a\nspecial meeting on Monday, March\n14, to further plans for construc\ntion of a building.\nAppointment of Kenneth Donly,\nRed Lodge, as fire truck driver was\ngiven approval. Donly was endors\ned by the Red Lodge Volunteer\nFire department.\nAll councilmen and mayor were\npresent.\nDOGS POISONED\nAn epidemic of dog poisoning\nhas again broken out in Red Lodge\nand persons owning dogs are warn\ned to be on the lookout for a dead\nly potion of poison being strewed\nabout the city. Several dog fanciers\nhave reported deaths.\nLAST RITES FOR\nMRS. KOSKI SET\nFinal rites for Mrs. Selma Kos\nki, 42, will be held from the Olcott\nFuneral Home Chapel at 2 p. m.\ntoday, The Rev. A. B. Cornelson\nofficiating. Burial will be in Red\nLodge cemetery.\nMrs. Koski succumbed at the\nNorth Haggin family home at ap\nproximately 11:45 a. m. Tuesday.\nSurvivors include her father and\nstepmother, Mr. and Mrs. John\nStone of Virginia, Minn.; a daugh\nter, Gertrude Koski, Red Lodge,\nand a son, Donald Koski, Red\nLodge. Mrs. Stone arrived here to\nattend the funeral.\nMrs. Koski was born in Sand\nCoulee, Mont., in 1896. Her hus\nband, K. N. Koski, preceded her in\ndeath three years ago.\nMORMON CRICKET\nAND AGRICULTURE\nPROGRAM IS SET\nWill Explain Detailed\nPlans at County\nGatherings\nAn effort will be made to explain\nboth the Agricultural Conservation\nprogram with its latest specifica\ntions in detail to all farmers of\nCarbon County in 6 district meet\nings, and the Mormon Cricket sit\nuation and set up will be given\nwith as much detail as possible for\nthe benefit of all communities to\nbe affected. These meetings will be\nheld as follows:\nLuther, Anderson's Hall, Mon\nday, March 14 at 1:15 p. m.; Red\nLodge, Court Room, Monday,\nMarch 14 at 7:00 p. m.; Bridger,\nTown Hall, Tuesday, March 15 at\n1:15 p. m.; Fromberg, Theatre,\nTuesday, March 15 at 7:00 p. m.;\nRoberts, High School Gym, Wed\nnesday, March 16, at 1:15 p. m.,\nand Joliet, High School, Wednes\nday, March 16 at 7:00 p. m.\nOn account of recent legislation\nall whether participating\nin the Conservation program or\nnot, should attempt to learn as\nmuch of the agricultural legisla\ntion as possible and find out how\nit applies to Carbon County and to\ntheir own individual farms.\nThe Mormon Cricket set up will\nbe considerably differ-ent from\nwhat it was in 1937 and all far\nmers who may be affected should\nbe present so that the proper\nsteps may be taken in getting the\ncounty organized in the way that\nthe crickets can be combated to the\nbest advantage under the program\nas outlined for this year. Meetings\nwill start on the dot since it will\ntake considerable time to get these\nprograms before the farmers.\nAll farmers in the Clarks Fork\nValley are urged to have their\nditches and canals on the east side\ncleaned at as early a date as pos\nsible so that the water may be\nturned in to help control cricket\ninvasion if it should develop at an\nearly season. Since other methods\nwill have to be relied upon for the\nwest side of the county, this plan\nis not as workable as it is in the\neast side.\nGRAPPLERS PLEASE\nCROWD WEDNESDAY\nAlthough Roughhouse Olsen,\nhuge Scandinavian grappler, had\nReferee Billy Hyde to contend with\nas well as his opponent, he had\nlittle trouble taking two straight\nfalls from Joe Reno in the second\nof a series of wrestling matches at\nWashington Hall Wednesday night.\nThe match was fairly well at\ntended, despite the fact there were\nother attractions in the city.\nNoticeable was a sprinkling of\nfeminine fans who seem to take\nan interest in the wrestling cards\nbeing arranged by the American\nLegion post here.\nOlsen cautioned Hyde to stay out\nof his way while he worked on the\nsmaller Reno, but Billy wasn't to\nbe shunted away in that manner\nso he took matters into his own\nhands, literally speaking. The Red\nLodge boxer promptly threw\nRoughhouse out of the ring, much\nto the delight of the onlookers.\nOlsen tried to make himself out\na bad man as he repeatedly placed\nhis fingers in Reno's eyes.\nThe victor won both falls with\na scissors body slam, taking the\nfirst decision in 10 minutes and the\nsecond in 12 minutes.\nVic Garbo had too much power\nfor Mike Caddock, in the semi\nwindup, taking two straight falls,\nthe first with a body twist and the\nsecond by way of a body slam.\nIn the opener Nick Bozinis and\nFloyd Britt flailed away 30 min\nutes to a draw.\nThe card was tamer than the\nfirst one held here, but packed in\nplenty of excitement, nevertheless,\nLeland Newman, commander of\nthe American Legion, announced\nthat a show would be held every\nWednesday until further notice.\nNewman announced the card for\nnext Wednesday night at Wash\nington Hall.\nFeatured in the main event, best\ntwo falls out of three will be\nYoung (Roughhouse Olsen) and\nVic Garbo. Nick Bozinis and Mike\nCaddock will tangle in he 45 min\nute semi-windup of two falls,\nwhile a new face appears in the\n30 minute-one fall opener. It's a\nnew face, if you could only see it,\nbut the whiskers owned by Ken\ntucky Hermit rather obliterates\nthe view. Hermit takes on Floyd\nBritt.","height":"22332","width":"16773"}}
